  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What is the difference between enum, union and struct in C programming?",
  "response": "In C programming, `enum`, `union`, and `struct` are three different ways to define custom data types, each with its specific purpose and behavior. Here's a detailed explanation of each:\n\n---\n\n### 1. **`enum` (Enumeration)**\n- **Purpose**: Used to define a set of named integer constants, making the code more readable and maintainable.\n- **Behavior**: Each named constant in an `enum` is assigned an integer value, starting from `0` by default. You can explicitly assign values if needed.\n- **Example**:\n\n  ```c\n  enum Colors {\n      RED,    // 0\n      GREEN,  // 1\n      BLUE    // 2\n  };\n\n  enum Colors color = GREEN;\n  printf(\"%d\\n\", color); // Output: 1\n  ```\n\n- **Key Features**:\n  - Enums are type-safe integer constants.\n  - Useful for representing a finite set of related values.\n\n---\n\n### 2. **`union`**\n- **Purpose**: Allows you to store different data types in the same memory location, but only one member can be active at a time.\n- **Behavior**: All members of a `union` share the same memory space, which is the size of the largest member.\n- **Example**:\n\n  ```c\n  union Data {\n      int i;\n      float f;\n      char str[20];\n  };\n\n  union Data data;\n  data.i = 10;\n  printf(\"%d\\n\", data.i); // Output: 10\n  data.f = 3.14;\n  printf(\"%f\\n\", data.f); // Output: 3.14\n  ```\n\n- **Key Features**:\n  - Saves memory by sharing memory space.\n  - Only one member can hold a value at any given time.\n\n---\n\n### 3. **`struct` (Structure)**\n- **Purpose**: Groups multiple variables (of potentially different data types) into a single composite data type.\n- **Behavior**: Each member of a `struct` has its own memory location. The size of the `struct` is the sum of the sizes of its members (plus padding for alignment).\n- **Example**:\n\n  ```c\n  struct Student {\n      int roll_no;\n      char name[50];\n      float marks;\n  };\n\n  struct Student student1;\n  student1.roll_no = 101;\n  strcpy(student1.name, \"John\");\n  student1.marks = 95.5;\n  printf(\"%d %s %.2f\\n\", student1.roll_no, student1.name, student1.marks);\n  ```\n\n- **Key Features**:\n  - Useful for storing related data as a single unit.\n  - Members are stored in separate memory locations.\n\n---\n\n### **Comparison Table**\n\n| Feature                | `enum`                          | `union`                          | `struct`                       |\n|------------------------|----------------------------------|----------------------------------|--------------------------------|\n| **Purpose**            | Define named integer constants  | Share memory for different types | Group related data             |\n| **Memory Usage**       | Minimal (size of `int`)         | Size of the largest member       | Sum of all members (+ padding) |\n| **Active Members**     | N/A (constants, not variables)  | Only one member at a time        | All members at once            |\n| **Use Case**           | Represent fixed set of values   | Save memory with type variants  | Organize complex data          |\n\n---\n\n### **Summary**\n- Use `enum` for defining a set of named integer constants.\n- Use `union` when you need to save memory by sharing storage for different data types.\n- Use `struct` to group multiple related variables into a single data type.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
